-- 5.6.1 Access Control Models
-- ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
INSERT INTO library_topics (
  domain_id, topic_number, title, one_liner, content_markdown,
  key_formulas, comparison_table, exam_tips, think_like_manager,
  memory_hack, memory_anchor
) VALUES (
  5,
  '5.6.1',
  'Access Control Models',
  'MAC enforces system-wide classification labels centrally; DAC lets resource owners grant permissions; RBAC assigns permissions to roles rather than individuals; ABAC uses policy rules combining multiple attributes — with RBAC being the enterprise default and ABAC the most granular and flexible.',
  '## Access Control Models

Access control models define who can access what resources and under what conditions. The choice of access control model has fundamental implications for how permissions are granted, managed, and revoked. NIST SP 800-162 provides guidance on Attribute-Based Access Control, and NIST RBAC model guidelines are foundational to most enterprise implementations.

### MAC: Mandatory Access Control

In **Mandatory Access Control**, access decisions are made by the system based on security labels attached to both subjects (users/processes) and objects (data/resources), according to a policy that users cannot override. A subject can only access an object if the system''s security policy permits the combination of the subject''s clearance and the object''s classification label.

MAC is **mandatory** because no individual user or resource owner can grant access that the policy does not permit — the policy is enforced centrally and cannot be overridden. MAC is used in high-security government and military environments where strict need-to-know must be enforced regardless of individual user decisions. The Bell-LaPadula model (no read up, no write down) is the theoretical basis for MAC in classified systems. Modern MAC implementations include SELinux and AppArmor on Linux, which enforce mandatory policies on process and file access.

### DAC: Discretionary Access Control

In **Discretionary Access Control**, the resource owner (the user who created or owns a resource) has discretion over who else can access it and what permissions they have. The classic example is a standard file system: the file creator sets read, write, and execute permissions for owner, group, and others (Unix/Linux permission model), or uses Access Control Lists (ACLs) to grant specific permissions to specific users (Windows NTFS). If the owner wants to grant a colleague access, they can do so without central authorization.

DAC is flexible and intuitive — resource owners manage their own data. Its weakness is that it is susceptible to Trojan horse attacks: a malicious program running as a user inherits all of that user''s permissions, including permissions to all files the user has DAC access to.

### RBAC: Role-Based Access Control

In **Role-Based Access Control**, permissions are assigned to roles rather than to individual users, and users are assigned to roles. A user''s effective access is the sum of permissions from all roles assigned to them. RBAC simplifies permission management enormously in large organizations: when a new employee joins the security operations team, they are added to the "SOC Analyst" role rather than having individual permissions configured. When their role changes, removing them from the role removes all associated permissions simultaneously.

NIST RBAC model (ANSI/INCITS 359-2004) defines four levels: Flat RBAC (basic user-role-permission assignment), Hierarchical RBAC (roles inherit from parent roles, e.g., "Senior Analyst" inherits all "Analyst" permissions), Constrained RBAC (adds separation of duty constraints — no user can be assigned to roles that would conflict), and Symmetric RBAC (full permissions management through roles).

RBAC is the dominant model in enterprise IT — Active Directory security groups, cloud IAM roles (AWS IAM, Azure RBAC), and enterprise applications all implement RBAC.

### ABAC: Attribute-Based Access Control

**Attribute-Based Access Control** makes access decisions based on policy rules that evaluate multiple attributes simultaneously: subject attributes (role, department, clearance level, training completion), object attributes (classification, sensitivity, data owner, creation date), environmental attributes (time of day, network location, authentication strength), and action (read, write, delete). ABAC is the most flexible and granular access control model — it can express access policies like "users in the Finance department with a SOX training completion certificate may modify budget records during business hours from corporate network IP ranges."

ABAC uses a policy decision point (PDP) that evaluates the policy rules and a policy enforcement point (PEP) that enforces the PDP''s decision. The XACML (eXtensible Access Control Markup Language) standard defines an XML-based policy language for ABAC. Cloud IAM systems increasingly support ABAC through tag-based policies and conditions. NIST SP 800-162 provides guidance on ABAC implementation.',
  NULL,
  '{"headers": ["Model", "Who Decides Access?", "Policy Flexibility", "Scalability", "Trojan Horse Resistance", "Primary Use Case"], "rows": [["MAC", "System enforces centrally; users cannot override", "Low (system policy fixed by administrators)", "Good (policy applies uniformly)", "High (policy enforced regardless of user action)", "Government/military classified systems, high-assurance OS (SELinux)"], ["DAC", "Resource owner grants permissions", "High (owner has full discretion)", "Poor (ad hoc permissions proliferate)", "Low (malware inherits user''s permissions)", "Standard OS file systems; small-scale resource sharing"], ["RBAC", "Administrators assign roles; roles have permissions", "Medium (role definitions controlled by admins)", "Good (one role change affects all members)", "Medium (roles reduce granular permission proliferation)", "Enterprise IT (Active Directory groups, cloud IAM roles, ERP access)"], ["ABAC", "Policy rules evaluate multiple attributes dynamically", "Very High (fine-grained, context-aware policies)", "Complex to manage; good at scale with automation", "High (context conditions limit exposure)", "Zero Trust architectures, cloud-native IAM, microservices access control"]]}'::jsonb,
  'Access control model exam areas: (1) MAC = system-enforced, security labels, no user override (government/military). (2) DAC = owner decides (flexible, Trojan horse risk). (3) RBAC = roles hold permissions; users get roles (enterprise standard). (4) ABAC = attributes + policy rules (most flexible, most granular). (5) The classic trap: "Discretionary" means the owner has discretion — not that it is optional. (6) MAC requires lattice-based labels (Bell-LaPadula compatible). RBAC supports separation of duty constraints in constrained RBAC.',
  'As a manager, RBAC should be the default model for enterprise access management. The practical benefit is reviewability: during an access review or audit, you review roles and their members rather than individual permissions for every user. When an employee changes departments, a role change propagates immediately. The failure mode of RBAC is role explosion — organizations that create one role per person have implemented DAC with extra steps. Establish role governance: define roles by function, not by individual, and review role membership quarterly.',
  'MDRА — Mandatory (centrally enforced labels), Discretionary (owner decides), Role-based (roles hold permissions, users get roles), Attribute-based (policy evaluates multiple attributes). Ascending flexibility and granularity: MAC (rigid) → DAC (owner''s choice) → RBAC (role-organized) → ABAC (any attribute, any policy). Think of MAC as the military officer who cannot share classified docs regardless of what the general says. DAC = your Google Drive file, your choice. RBAC = job title = access level. ABAC = multiple factors evaluated per request.',
  'In the London Office IAM room, four access control systems are shown on the architecture diagram. The classified document vault uses MAC (SELinux enforces security labels — not even the vault administrator can move a Top Secret file to an Unclassified share). The old HR file server uses DAC (each manager owns their team''s folder and controls access manually — a mess of ad-hoc permissions). The ERP system uses RBAC (Finance Analyst role, Finance Manager role, AP Clerk role — adding a new employee assigns them to their role). The new cloud data platform uses ABAC (a policy: "if subject.department=Finance AND object.classification<=Confidential AND time=BusinessHours AND location=CorporateNetwork, PERMIT READ").'
);

